1 "§ 126A-24. State of the State Workforce Report.
2 (a) Beginning January 15, 2027, and annually thereafter, OSHR shall report on the state
3 of the state employee workforce and statewide human resources programs to the Joint Legislative
4 Commission on Governmental Operations, the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on
5 General Government, the Fiscal Research Division, and the Appropriations Committees of the
6 House of Representatives and the Senate. This report shall include:
7 (1) A comparison of state employee compensation rates and benefits compared to
8 national trends. The report shall include at least the following:
9 a. An overview of economic conditions and labor market trends,
10 b. An analysis of the competitiveness of state salary and benefits,
11 c. A review of recruitment and retention efforts and results, and
12 d. The results of the annual compensation surveys conducted pursuant to
13 subsection (b) of this section.
14 (2) The safety, health, and workers' compensation activities of State agencies in
15 compliance with G.S. 143-583 and the fines levied against State agencies
16 pursuant to Article 16 of Chapter 95 of the General Statutes;
17 (3) The costs associated with the defense or settlement of administrative
18 grievances and lawsuits filed by current or former State employees and
19 applicants for State employment;
20 (4) Agency compliance with Temporary Solutions policies and rules adopted
21 pursuant to N.C.G.S. § 126-6.3, including:
22 a. The number and type of all exceptions made by the Director of the
23 OSHR.
24 b. A list of agencies with invoices with due dates greater than 60 days.
25 c. A list of agencies with temporary employees who exceeded 11 months
26 of consecutive employment, including a count of employees who
27 exceed 11 months of consecutive employment, and the average
28 number of days employees exceeded this limit.
29 (b) To guide the Governor and the General Assembly in making decisions regarding the
30 compensation of State employees, the OSHR shall conduct annual compensation surveys. The
31 Commission shall present the results of the compensation survey as part of the report under
32 subsection (a) of this section.
33 "§§ 126A-25 through 126A-29. Reserved for future codification purposes.
34 "Article 3.
35 "Classification and Minimum Qualifications.
36 "§ 126A-30. Commission oversight of classification system; minimum job qualifications.
37 (a) Subject to the approval of the Governor, the Commission may establish policies or
38 rules governing each of the following including but not limited to:
39 (1) Position classification plans which provide for the classification and
40 reclassification, or other grouping of positions subject to this Article according
41 to the duties and responsibilities of the positions.
42 (2) For each group of positions, reasonable minimum qualifications as to
43 education, experience, specialized training, licenses, certifications, and other
44 job-related requirements pertinent to the work to be performed.
45 (3) The process of position classification and reclassification.
46 (4) Procedures for hiring employees on the basis of specific demonstrated
47 competencies, rather than years of experience or education.
48 (b) The Commission may prepare a classification system that organizes positions in state
49 government into a classification, based on their duties and responsibilities. Classifications may
50 be grouped, subdivided, ranked, or otherwise organized in such manner as the Commission
51 deems appropriate.
