19 (c) The legislative and judicial branches shall adopt parental leave policies.
20 "§ 126A-71. Paid parental leave.
21 (a) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
22 (1) Child. – A newborn biological child or a newly placed adopted, foster, or
23 otherwise legally placed child under the age of 18 whose parent is a State
24 employee eligible for leave under subsection (b) of this section.
25 (2) Parent. – Includes a parent by adoption, foster care, or another legal
26 placement.
27 (3) Qualifying event. – When a State employee becomes a parent to a child.
28 (b) Paid Parental Leave. – The Commission shall adopt rules and policies to provide that
29 a permanent, probationary, or time-limited full-time State employee may take the following paid
30 parental leave:
31 (1) Up to twelve weeks of paid leave after giving birth to a child; or
32 (2) Up to twelve weeks of paid leave after any other qualifying event.
33 (c) Rulemaking – The Commission shall adopt rules and policies to provide for:
34 (1) A part-time permanent or time-limited State employee to be able to take a
35 prorated amount of paid leave, not to exceed twelve weeks after giving birth
36 or after any other qualifying event.
37 (2) A period of minimum service before an employee becomes eligible for paid
38 leave under this section, which must credit employees for aggregate service
39 in an agency, excluding the legislative and judicial branches, community
40 college located in this State, and public school unit that provides paid parental
41 leave in accordance with this section.
42 (3) A maximum number of uses of paid parental leave within a 12-month period.
43 (4) Available leave amounts following a miscarriage or death of a child during
44 birth
45 (d) Requirements. – The paid parental leave authorized by this section:
46 (1) Is available without exhaustion of the employee's sick and vacation leave and
47 is awarded in addition to shared leave under G.S. 126A-75, or other leave
48 authorized by State or federal law.
49 (2) Has no cash value upon termination from employment.
50 (3) May not be used for calculating an employee's retirement benefits.
